{"cursor":"14751","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'checked tone', commonly known by its Chinese calque 'entering tone' (, lit.\n'The tone of Chinese Character 'å¥'), is one of four syllable types in the\nphonology in Middle Chinese which are commonly translated as tone. However, it\nis not a tone in the phonetic sense, but rather describes a syllable that ends\nin a stop consonant, such as p, t, k, or glottal stop. Note that separating the\nchecked tone allows us to treat -p, -t, and -k as allophones of -m, -n, and -ng\nrespectively because they are in a complementary distribution in which stops\nappear only in the checked tone while nasals appear only in other tones. Due to\nthe origin of tone in Chinese, the number of tones found in such syllables is\nsmaller than the number of tones in other syllables, and in Chinese phonetics\nthey have traditionally been counted separately. For instance, in Cantonese,\nthere are 6 tones in syllables which do not end in stops, but only three in\nsyllables which do; therefore, although Cantonese only has 6 tones in the sense\nof 6 contrasting variations in pitch, it is often said to have 9.\n\nFinal stops, and therefore the checked \"tones\", have disappeared from most\nMandarin dialects (a large dialect chain spoken in northern and southwestern\nChina), but remain preserved in southeastern Chinese languages such as\nCantonese, Min, and Hakka.\n\nTones are an indispensable part of Chinese literature, as characters in poetry\nand prose were chosen according to tones and rhymes for their euphony. This use\nof language helps in reconstructing the pronunciation of Old Chinese and Middle\nChinese, since the Chinese writing system is logographic rather than phonetic.\n","linknr":238,"url":"entering","recorded":1363419094,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Checked_tone&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Checked_tone&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/op